Context:
The `deriveMatchPattern` function at line 29-36 currently does:
```ts
const deriveMatchPattern = (urlString: string): string | null => {
  try {
    const url = new URL(urlString);
    return `*://${url.hostname}/*`;
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
};
```

This drops the port entirely. Chrome match patterns support ports: `*://hostname:port/*` is valid.

Changes:
Change to include the port when it's non-standard. `new URL()` exposes `.host` (hostname:port) and `.hostname` (hostname only). Use `.host` which includes the port when present, but omit the port for standard 80/443.

```ts
const deriveMatchPattern = (urlString: string): string | null => {
  try {
    const url = new URL(urlString);
    // url.host includes port when non-default; url.hostname does not.
    // For standard ports (80/443), url.host === url.hostname (port is stripped).
    return `*://${url.host}/*`;
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
};
```

Note: `new URL('http://localhost:3000').host` returns `'localhost:3000'`. `new URL('https://example.com').host` returns `'example.com'` (443 is the default for https, so it's stripped). `new URL('http://example.com').host` returns `'example.com'` (80 is the default for http, so it's stripped). This is exactly the behavior we want — Chrome match patterns work the same way.

Update existing unit tests — many currently expect `*://hostname/*` for URLs with ports. The test at line 30 for `'https://my-app.example.com/dashboard'` should still produce `*://my-app.example.com/*` (no port). But if we had a test with `http://localhost:3000`, it should now produce `*://localhost:3000/*`.

Existing tests that need updating (check each test's input URL and expected pattern):
- 'derives match pattern from single-instance url map' (line 25) — input `'https://my-app.example.com/dashboard'` → no change (standard port)
- 'derives match patterns from multi-instance url map' (line 38) — inputs are `https://prod.example.com` and `https://staging.example.com` → no change
- 'appends derived patterns to static urlPatterns' (line 64) — `https://custom.example.com` → no change
- All other tests use standard-port URLs, so most won't change.

Add new tests for:
- `http://localhost:3000/app` → `*://localhost:3000/*`
- `http://127.0.0.1:8080` → `*://127.0.0.1:8080/*`
- `http://localhost:80` → `*://localhost/*` (explicit standard port is stripped by URL constructor)
- `https://example.com:443` → `*://example.com/*` (explicit standard port is stripped)
- `http://example.com:8443/path` → `*://example.com:8443/*`

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the function signature or return type
- Do NOT change how invalid URLs are handled (return null)
- The instanceMap values will now include ports where applicable — this is intentional and needed for downstream matching

